

#include "ModFeedback.hpp"

/*
AILEARNINGS
Symptom (subtitle_test): Mod subtitle messages were "sent" (logs) but nothing showed in the HMD.
Trace evidence: our ProcessEvent target object was the CDO: `BP_RadiusPlayerCharacter_Gameplay.Default__BP_RadiusPlayerCharacter_Gameplay_C`.
Counter-evidence: game-generated empty-gun warning called the same `ShowSubtitles` function on the live in-level actor: `L_Forest.L_Forest.PersistentLevel.BP_RadiusPlayerCharacter_Gameplay_C_...`.
Root cause: our player lookup could return the class default object (CDO) via a naive GObjects scan fallback; calling gameplay events (like `ShowSubtitles`) on the CDO is a no-op.
Fix: `GameContext::GetPlayerCharacter()` now filters out default objects (`UObject::IsDefaultObject()`), prefers `PlayerController -> Pawn` / GameplayStatics paths, and only uses a world-matching scan as a last resort.
String lifetime gotcha: Dumper-7 `SDK::FString` is a non-owning view; pointing it at temporary buffers can UAF in deferred UI paths.
Fix: build messages in `std::wstring` and use a thread-local ring of backing buffers (`MakeStableFString`).
Symptom (media playback): `media_file` / `media_url` / `playrandomsound` reported generic "media play failed" and produced no audible output.
Root cause: 2D media path instantiated a `UMediaPlayer` but did not reliably provide an audio sink component in-world, and diagnostics did not surface the player's runtime state.
Fix: spawn and register a `UMediaSoundComponent` attached to player root for 2D media playback, set `PlayOnOpen`, and include detailed player state (`ready/preparing/buffering/connecting/playing/url/player`) in logs and command errors.
Symptom (3D media crashes 2026-02-26): Friend NPCs with attached 3D audio caused intermittent crashes shortly after media playback started.
Root cause: Media components attached to actors were not cleaned up when actors became invalid or were destroyed. The gActiveMedia vector accumulated stale references with dangling actor pointers.
Fix: Added CleanupStaleMedia() function called from DrainPending() every frame. It checks each media instance for invalid players, invalid owner actors (for 3D attached audio), and naturally finished playback. Stale instances are properly closed (Player->Close()), components destroyed (K2_DestroyComponent), and removed from the tracking vector.
Additional timing fix: do not clean up newly-started players while they are still preparing. Each media entry records a start time and retains itself for at least kMediaStaleCleanupDelaySeconds before being eligible for automatic removal.
Symptom (3D audio not spatializing 2026-02-26): 3D audio attached to friend NPCs sounded centered on the player (equal volume in both ears) even when NPC was 3000 units away.
Root cause: SpawnAttachedMediaSoundComponent enabled bAllowSpatialization but did not configure attenuation settings. Without attenuation overrides, the sound component used default settings (no distance falloff).
Fix: Set bOverrideAttenuation = true and configured AttenuationOverrides struct with: bAttenuate=true, bSpatialize=true, Linear distance algorithm, Sphere shape, FalloffDistance=5000 units, dBAttenuationAtMax=-60dB. Also added low-pass filtering (bAttenuateWithLPF=true, LPF kicks in at 1000 units, fully muffled by 5000 units) for distance realism.
Symptom (wav cleanup too early 2026-02-26): `CleanupStaleWav` freed newly triggered ambient WAV instances within ~30-50ms of `PlayWavAttachedToActor ok`, often before audible playback.
Root cause: WAV startup grace used world-time lookups from component context (`GetTimeSeconds`) which can be inconsistent during spawn/registration timing; this made grace checks unreliable and cleanup could treat new entries as stale.
Fix: switched WAV startup grace tracking to monotonic tick time (`GetTickCount64` via `NowTickMs`) and added reason-rich cleanup diagnostics (actor invalid / component invalid / not playing, plus age and descriptor) to make one VR run conclusive.
Symptom (component-invalid in ~16ms 2026-02-26): even with WAV grace logging, `CleanupStaleWav` reported `component-invalid` almost immediately after successful spawn logs.
Root cause: non-looping attached WAVs were spawned with `bAutoDestroy=true`; if startup hiccups occurred, the component could self-destruct before we observed stable playback, collapsing diagnosis into early invalidation.
Fix: force attached WAV audio components to stay alive (`bAutoDestroy=false` path) and only treat `component-invalid` as terminal after WAV grace expires; added startup-state logs around `Play()` for decisive one-run diagnostics.
Symptom (wav still silent 2026-02-26): components stayed valid at start but cleanup removed entries at ~1000ms with `not-playing-after-grace` even for 3-5s clips.
Root cause: cleanup relied on `UAudioComponent::IsPlaying()` too early; for this spawned raw-PCM path, `IsPlaying()` can drop false before expected clip completion.
Fix: cleanup is now duration-aware for non-looping WAVs (retain until parsed duration + slack) and only treats `!IsPlaying()` as terminal after that window.
Symptom (insufficient troubleshooting signal 2026-02-26): iterative VR runs still lacked decisive object-level telemetry for spawned WAV audio components.
Root cause: logs were outcome-focused (success/freed) but did not frontload full component state (play state enum, ownership/attachment, flags, attenuation pointers) at spawn and over early lifetime.
Fix: added structured `WAV_DIAG` dumps at spawn and staged lifecycle checkpoints so one run captures full object state transitions.
Symptom (wav silent with valid component 2026-02-26): diagnostics showed `compPlayState=1` while component/object references stayed valid for full expected duration.
Root cause: in UE enum `EAudioComponentPlayState`, value `1` is `Stopped`; this confirms an actual early stop state, and `IsPlaying()` alone is too weak/noisy as a primary decision signal.
Fix: switched WAV "active" checks to use `GetPlayState()` semantics (Playing/FadingIn/FadingOut/Paused) and added human-readable play-state names in all WAV diagnostics.
Symptom (raw-PCM USoundWave silent 2026-02-26): WAV audio components had valid resources and stayed alive but `GetPlayState()` showed `Stopped` immediately after `Play()` call.
Root cause: in UE5, raw PCM written directly to USoundWave memory offsets (RawPCMData/RawPCMDataSize at 0x03A0/0x03A8) is not automatically recognized by the audio engine. The audio mixdown must be triggered through proper UE5 APIs, not raw memory writes.
Fix: implemented USynthSamplePlayer-based 3D audio path. USynthSamplePlayer is from the Synthesis plugin and inherits from USynthComponent which has native 3D spatial audio support. Workflow:
1. Parse WAV and load into USoundWave via LoadWavAsSoundWave()
2. Spawn USynthSamplePlayer via NewObject and attach to actor via K2_AttachToComponent
3. Configure 3D attenuation on the synth component (bAllowSpatialization, bOverrideAttenuation, AttenuationOverrides)
4. Call synthPlayer->SetSoundWave(sw) to assign the sample
5. Call synthPlayer->Start() to begin playback
This path uses proper UE5 runtime audio APIs rather than raw memory manipulation, ensuring the audio engine recognizes the sample data.
Update (2026-02-26): USynthSamplePlayer.SetSoundWave with raw-PCM-loaded USoundWave does NOT produce audible audio. IsPlaying() returns true but no sound is heard. The engine likely expects the USoundWave to be loaded through proper asset import pipeline.
Current working approach: UMediaPlayer + UMediaSoundComponent (extends USynthComponent, so it has native 3D spatial capabilities via bAllowSpatialization, bOverrideAttenuation, AttenuationOverrides). This produces audible sound from filesystem files via OpenFile().
Game reference: MicrophoneSpeakComponent uses USoundWaveProcedural + UAudioComponent for working 3D voice audio, but takes opus-encoded data rather than raw PCM.
*/

